{"type":"message","id":"c90b2343","parentId":"433a6a22","timestamp":"2026-04-10T16:30:32.056Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"No CRON-CONTEXT.md file exists, but I have the context from the cron trigger - I need to send a bedtime story to the group. Let me search for a compelling true story to share.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_nfel11hw2f1w_1","name":"web_search","arguments":{"count":5,"query":"inspiring true story historical event life lesson goodnight story"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"kilocode","model":"kilo-auto/free","usage":{"input":107,"output":132,"cacheRead":18304,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":18543,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775838620139,"responseId":"gen-1775838620-vZ6yR54s0M3DsXHxx8GH"}}
{"type":"message","id":"730ae542","parentId":"c90b2343","timestamp":"2026-04-10T16:30:43.279Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_nfel11hw2f1w_1","toolName":"web_search","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"query\": \"inspiring true story historical event life lesson goodnight story\",\n  \"provider\": \"gemini\",\n  \"model\": \"gemini-2.5-flash\",\n  \"tookMs\": 11211,\n  \"externalContent\": {\n    \"untrusted\": true,\n    \"source\": \"web_search\",\n    \"provider\": \"gemini\",\n    \"wrapped\": true\n  },\n  \"content\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"f3307fb8956bd26a\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nOnce upon a time, not so long ago, in a quiet town in Tennessee, a little girl named Wilma was born. But Wilma's start in life was very, very tough. When she was just a tiny baby, she became very sick with diseases like double pneumonia and scarlet fever. These illnesses left her with a paralyzed leg, and the doctors sadly told her mother that Wilma might never walk again.\\n\\nImagine, little Wilma had to wear a metal brace on her leg just to move around, and even then, walking was incredibly difficult. But Wilma had a spark inside her, a determined spirit that refused to give up. Every week, her mother would take her on a long bus ride for physical therapy, and Wilma, with a brave heart, would try her very best to move her leg. It was slow, hard work, but Wilma never stopped trying.\\n\\nBy the time she was nine years old, something amazing happened: Wilma was able to remove her metal brace! And by age thirteen, she had developed a rhythmic walk, a beautiful rhythm that hinted at the incredible things to come. It was then that she decided she wanted to be a runner.\\n\\nAt first, Wilma entered every race she could, and do you know what happened? She came in last. Every single time! People told her to quit, that running wasn't for her, but Wilma just shook her head. She remembered all the hard work it took to learn to walk, and she knew in her heart that if she kept trying, she could do it. She kept running, and running, and training, and running some more.\\n\\nAnd then, one magical day, Wilma won a race! From that day forward, her determination shone even brighter. She went on to win every race she entered, eventually competing in the Olympic Games. There, the little girl who was once told she would never walk again, ran faster than anyone else in the world, winning three gleaming gold medals!\\n\\nSo, as you snuggle into bed tonight, remember Wilma's incredible story. It teaches us that even when things are incredibly difficult, and even when others doubt us, with perseverance, hard work, and a brave heart, we can overcome our challenges and achieve our biggest dreams. Sweet dreams!\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"f3307fb8956bd26a\\\">>>\",\n  \"citations\": [\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://medium.com/@inspiringlifewithfrances/50-inspirational-stories-of-people-who-never-gave-up-eab3b8486f67\",\n      \"title\": \"medium.com\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://listverse.com/2023/05/14/10-inspiring-stories-of-people-who-overcame-adversity/\",\n      \"title\": \"listverse.com\"\n    }\n  ]\n}"}],"details":{"query":"inspiring true story historical event life lesson goodnight story","provider":"gemini","model":"gemini-2.5-flash","tookMs":11211,"externalContent":{"untrusted":true,"source":"web_search","provider":"gemini","wrapped":true},"content":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"f3307fb8956bd26a\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nOnce upon a time, not so long ago, in a quiet town in Tennessee, a little girl named Wilma was born. But Wilma's start in life was very, very tough. When she was just a tiny baby, she became very sick with diseases like double pneumonia and scarlet fever. These illnesses left her with a paralyzed leg, and the doctors sadly told her mother that Wilma might never walk again.\n\nImagine, little Wilma had to wear a metal brace on her leg just to move around, and even then, walking was incredibly difficult. But Wilma had a spark inside her, a determined spirit that refused to give up. Every week, her mother would take her on a long bus ride for physical therapy, and Wilma, with a brave heart, would try her very best to move her leg. It was slow, hard work, but Wilma never stopped trying.\n\nBy the time she was nine years old, something amazing happened: Wilma was able to remove her metal brace! And by age thirteen, she had developed a rhythmic walk, a beautiful rhythm that hinted at the incredible things to come. It was then that she decided she wanted to be a runner.\n\nAt first, Wilma entered every race she could, and do you know what happened? She came in last. Every single time! People told her to quit, that running wasn't for her, but Wilma just shook her head. She remembered all the hard work it took to learn to walk, and she knew in her heart that if she kept trying, she could do it. She kept running, and running, and training, and running some more.\n\nAnd then, one magical day, Wilma won a race! From that day forward, her determination shone even brighter. She went on to win every race she entered, eventually competing in the Olympic Games. There, the little girl who was once told she would never walk again, ran faster than anyone else in the world, winning three gleaming gold medals!\n\nSo, as you snuggle into bed tonight, remember Wilma's incredible story. It teaches us that even when things are incredibly difficult, and even when others doubt us, with perseverance, hard work, and a brave heart, we can overcome our challenges and achieve our biggest dreams. Sweet dreams!\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"f3307fb8956bd26a\">>>","citations":[{"url":"https://medium.com/@inspiringlifewithfrances/50-inspirational-stories-of-people-who-never-gave-up-eab3b8486f67","title":"medium.com"},{"url":"https://listverse.com/2023/05/14/10-inspiring-stories-of-people-who-overcame-adversity/","title":"listverse.com"}]},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775838643276}}
{"type":"message","id":"9c119eec","parentId":"730ae542","timestamp":"2026-04-10T16:30:48.588Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to send a bedtime story to a Telegram group. Let me craft a compelling, simple story based on the Wilma Rudolph search result. The story should be 8-12 lines, simple language, and end with a goodnight wish.\n\nLet me format this nicely as a Telegram message.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_eemi8jqhbo9s_1","name":"message","arguments":{"action":"send","channel":"telegram","message":"Once upon a time, a little girl named Wilma was born in Tennessee. When she was just a baby, she got very sick — double pneumonia and scarlet fever left her legs paralyzed. Doctors told her mother she might never walk again.\n\nShe had to wear a metal brace just to move. Every week, her mom took her on long bus rides for therapy. At age 9, she removed the brace. By 13, she developed a rhythmic walk.\n\nShe wanted to be a runner. She entered every race she could — and came in LAST every time. People told her to quit.\n\nBut she remembered how hard it was just to learn to walk. She kept running, training, trying.\n\nAnd then — she won. Then she won again. And again.\n\nThat little girl who was told she'd never walk became the fastest woman in the world, winning THREE Olympic gold medals.\n\nThe lesson? When life pushes you down, get back up. Keep going. Your breakthrough is coming.\n\nGoodnight! 🖤","target":"-1003606834639"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"kilocode","model":"kilo-auto/free","usage":{"input":793,"output":397,"cacheRead":18400,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":19590,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775838643280,"responseId":"gen-1775838643-qaz6xh2XbJwsvmKdwZKJ"}}
